        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>445</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0022</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0022.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Basis">Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0022.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In the context of functional analysis and Hilbert spaces, there are several different notions of a basis:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Orthonormal basis:</fr:strong> In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is called an orthonormal basis if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">complete</fr:link>, meaning that the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is the entire space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>. Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal basis if for every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex> (expansion formula)</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex></fr:li> (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link>)</fr:ul>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Schauder basis:</fr:strong> A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_i\}]]></fr:tex> in a Banach space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is called a Schauder basis if every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> can be expressed uniquely as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{i=1}^{\infty } a_i x_i]]></fr:tex>, where the coefficients <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i]]></fr:tex> are scalars and the series converges in the norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Hamel basis:</fr:strong> A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> in a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is called a Hamel basis if every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  V]]></fr:tex> can be expressed uniquely as a finite linear combination <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _{i=1}^n a_i e_i]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i]]></fr:tex> are scalars. This is the algebraic notion of a basis, but in <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0005.xml" addr="FA-0005" title="Infinite Dimensions">infinite-dimensional</fr:link> spaces, Hamel bases are typically not useful for analysis because they are uncountable and the expansions don't involve convergence of series.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal bases</fr:link> in Hilbert spaces, the existence of such bases is guaranteed by the Gram-Schmidt process and Zorn's lemma, though they may be uncountable for non-separable spaces.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>447</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0020</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0020.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0020.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{x_n : n âˆˆ N\}]]></fr:tex> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> H is <fr:em>complete (note that this is <fr:strong>not</fr:strong> in the sense of a complete metric <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link>)</fr:em>  if it satisfies <fr:em>any</fr:em> of the equivalent conditions (a)-(e) in <fr:strong>Theorem</fr:strong>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then the following conditions are equivalent:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(a)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_n, x \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(b)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} \langle  u_n, x \rangle  u_n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(c)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} |\langle  u_n, x \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>(This is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link>)</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(d)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[U] = H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(e)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0024.xml" addr="FA-0024" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Informally</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>For an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> in a Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to be a <fr:strong>basis</fr:strong> (or complete), it means that the set is "<fr:em>large enough</fr:em>" to represent any vector in the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> is <fr:em>complete</fr:em> if it's <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> is the whole space</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>449</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0024</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0024.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Maximal orthonormal set">Maximal orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0024.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is called maximal if there is no orthonormal set that properly contains <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is maximal if adding any non-zero vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  H \setminus  S]]></fr:tex> would destroy the orthonormality property. This means that for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  H]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||v|| = 1]]></fr:tex> that is not in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, there exists some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u \in  S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u, v \rangle  \neq  0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A key result in the theory of Hilbert spaces states that an orthonormal set is maximal if and only if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">complete</fr:link>, meaning that its <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> equals the entire Hilbert space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is maximal if and only if:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  x, e_i \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex> can be expressed as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link> holds: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>451</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000V</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000V.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthogonal complement">Orthogonal complement</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-000V.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a subset of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>. The orthogonal complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp ]]></fr:tex>, is the set of all vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> that are orthogonal to every vector in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp  = \{y \in  H : \langle  x, y \rangle  = 0 \text { for all } x \in  S\}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Some important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp ]]></fr:tex> is a closed subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(S^\perp )^\perp  = \overline {\text {span}(S)}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {\text {span}(S)}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H = \overline {\text {span}(S)} \oplus  S^\perp ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\oplus ]]></fr:tex> represents the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0015.xml" addr="FA-0015" title="Direct sum">direct sum</fr:link> of subspaces</fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>453</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0019</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0019.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0019.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An orthonormal basis for a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001H.xml" addr="FA-001H" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> of vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> such that the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is the entire space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, an orthonormal basis is an orthonormal set that is also <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> in the sense that any vector in the Hilbert space can be approximated arbitrarily well by finite linear combinations of the basis elements.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal basis of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> if and only if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Important properties include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Every Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis (this requires the <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0054">Axiom of Choice</fr:link> for general Hilbert spaces)</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link> holds for orthonormal bases</fr:li>
<fr:li>Any two orthonormal bases of the same Hilbert space have the same cardinality</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
