          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>455</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-000U.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>457</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001H</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001H.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal set">Orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-001H.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An orthonormal set in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a set of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> that satisfies the following conditions:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Each vector has unit norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||e_i|| = 1]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Different vectors are orthogonal to each other: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, an orthonormal set satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0011.xml" addr="FA-0011" title="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Orthonormal sets are fundamental building blocks in the theory of Hilbert spaces. They allow for simple representations of vectors:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal set and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is a vector in the Hilbert space, then the Fourier coefficients of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> with respect to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> are given by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c_i = \langle  v, e_i \rangle ]]></fr:tex>, and we can write:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _i c_i e_i + w]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> is orthogonal to the span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
